A '''family of musical instruments''' is a grouping of several different but related sizes or types of instruments. Some schemes of [[musical instrument classification]], such as the [[Hornbostel-Sachs]] system, are based on a hierarchy of instrument families and families of families.
Some commonly recognized families are: *[[Brass instrument|Brass]] family *[[String instrument|Strings]] family *[[Woodwind]] family *[[Percussion_instrument|Percussion]] family *[[Keyboard instrument|Keyboard]] family<ref>{{Cite web|title = Musical Instruments|url = http://www.naxos.com/education/music_instruments.asp|website = www.naxos.com|access-date = 2016-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Musical Instruments: Types & History - Video & Lesson Transcript {{!}} Study.com|url = http://study.com/academy/lesson/musical-instruments-types-history.html|website = Study.com|access-date = 2016-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Musical Instruments|url = http://exhibits.pacsci.org/music/Instruments.html|website = exhibits.pacsci.org|access-date = 2016-01-15}}</ref>
Family relationships are not always clear-cut. For example, some authorities regard families as encompassing only instruments of different pitch range that have similar construction and tone quality. They therefore, for example, do not regard the [[cor anglais]] as a member of the oboe family, because its narrow bore and piriform bell give it a distinctly different tone quality from the oboe.{{cn|date=November 2013}}
