{{Orphan|date=October 2018}}
'''Media ritual''' is a term used to describe a [[Theory|theoretical]] approach in the field of [[Media studies|media]] and [[Communication studies|communication]] studies, which borrows thematically from the field of [[anthropology]]. The theory is based upon [[James W. Carey|Carey]]'s 'ritual view of communication' in which he asserts that "news reading, and writing, is a ritual act and moreover a dramatic one'''.'''" (Carey, 1989<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AcSufbsE7TwC | title = Communication as Culture: Essays on Media and Society | last = Carey | first = James W. | date = 1989-01-01 | publisher = Psychology Press | isbn = 9780415907255 | language = en }}</ref>). This 'ritual' view of communication is in contrast to his 'transmission' view of communication. Media ritual theory has been elaborated in recent years, popularised in particular by Nick Couldry (e.g. Couldry, 2003<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=RslZmAEACAAJ | title = Media Rituals: A Critical Approach | last = Couldry | first = Nick | date = 2003-01-01 | publisher = Routledge | isbn = 9780415270144 | language = en }}</ref>).
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Sociological terminology]] [[Category:Communication]]
{{Anthropology-stub}}

{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}
{{italic title}}
'''''Mimesis''''' is a quarterly [[literary magazine]] based in [[Norwich]] that deals predominantly with [[poetry]]. The magazine was started in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=MIMESIS - website launch of new literary journal|url=http://poeticwar.deviantart.com/journal/MIMESIS-website-launch-of-new-literary-journal-214149686|work=Deviant Art|accessdate=17 August 2015|date=18 March 2007}}</ref>  Issues appear in January, April, July and November. The journal stands out for the number of pages filled purely by poems. An interview with a well-known poet is also featured in each issue. A small number of greyscale artworks appear alongside the writing. 

